Archaeological Documentation Point (adb)

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#adb
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#adb
Label Archaeological Documentation Point (adb)
Definition Archaeological Documentation Points (ADP) are an expanded description of 'trench' type documentation units that capture more detailed information about the circumstances of an excavation. Their main specificity is the option of assigning information about the captured stratigraphic horizons and their precise positional and elevation determination by means of so-called elevation points. These data allow reconstructing archaeological terrains and predicting the degree of their preservation in the surrounding area. The ADP registration system is based on the principles set by L. Hrdlička, who compiled and maintained the ADP Map for the Prague Conservation Area for a long time. The data in the AMCR are directly related to this registration system.
Hierarchy
  • profiles class Archaeological Documentation Point (adb) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#adb)
    Definition: Archaeological Documentation Points (ADP) are an expanded description of 'trench' type documentation units that capture more detailed information about the circumstances of an excavation. Their main specificity is the option of assigning information about the captured stratigraphic horizons and their precise positional and elevation determination by means of so-called elevation points. These data allow reconstructing archaeological terrains and predicting the degree of their preservation in the surrounding area. The ADP registration system is based on the principles set by L. Hrdlička, who compiled and maintained the ADP Map for the Prague Conservation Area for a long time. The data in the AMCR are directly related to this registration system.
    • specializes class dokumentacni_jednotka (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokumentacni_jednotka)
      • specializes class Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#archeologicky_zaznam)
        Definition: Archaeological records are a collective term for two types of records - archaeological FIELDWORK EVENTS and SITES. The archaeological record is further subdivided into spatial units, the so-called documentation units. A documentation unit can be considered to be the entire area of an event, its part corresponding to a certain group of finds, or its part defined by the course of fieldwork (e.g. a specific trench). Components are linked to documentation units. Components are determined by assignment to an activity area (a specific functional part of a settlement area) and period (a chronological and cultural classification). Each component is also assigned a list of activities, i.e., the types of activities that are directly documented within the component. Components are arbitrarily defined units; the decisive aspect in their definition is the clarity and understandability of the record of the event's results. In the AMCR, we do not envisage a detailed and exhaustive description of the archaeological finds belonging to each component; we understand finds only as specific attributes of components that help us to characterize the source material by which the component was recognized.

Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam)

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#archeologicky_zaznam
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#archeologicky_zaznam
Label Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam)
Definition Archaeological records are a collective term for two types of records - archaeological FIELDWORK EVENTS and SITES. The archaeological record is further subdivided into spatial units, the so-called documentation units. A documentation unit can be considered to be the entire area of an event, its part corresponding to a certain group of finds, or its part defined by the course of fieldwork (e.g. a specific trench). Components are linked to documentation units. Components are determined by assignment to an activity area (a specific functional part of a settlement area) and period (a chronological and cultural classification). Each component is also assigned a list of activities, i.e., the types of activities that are directly documented within the component. Components are arbitrarily defined units; the decisive aspect in their definition is the clarity and understandability of the record of the event's results. In the AMCR, we do not envisage a detailed and exhaustive description of the archaeological finds belonging to each component; we understand finds only as specific attributes of components that help us to characterize the source material by which the component was recognized.

chranene_udaje

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#chranene_udaje.adb
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#chranene_udaje.adb
Label chranene_udaje
Hierarchy
  • profiles class chranene_udaje (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#chranene_udaje.adb)
    • specializes class chranene_udaje (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#chranene_udaje)
    • specializes class Archaeological Documentation Point (adb) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#adb)
      Definition: Archaeological Documentation Points (ADP) are an expanded description of 'trench' type documentation units that capture more detailed information about the circumstances of an excavation. Their main specificity is the option of assigning information about the captured stratigraphic horizons and their precise positional and elevation determination by means of so-called elevation points. These data allow reconstructing archaeological terrains and predicting the degree of their preservation in the surrounding area. The ADP registration system is based on the principles set by L. Hrdlička, who compiled and maintained the ADP Map for the Prague Conservation Area for a long time. The data in the AMCR are directly related to this registration system.
      • specializes class dokumentacni_jednotka (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokumentacni_jednotka)
        • specializes class Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#archeologicky_zaznam)
          Definition: Archaeological records are a collective term for two types of records - archaeological FIELDWORK EVENTS and SITES. The archaeological record is further subdivided into spatial units, the so-called documentation units. A documentation unit can be considered to be the entire area of an event, its part corresponding to a certain group of finds, or its part defined by the course of fieldwork (e.g. a specific trench). Components are linked to documentation units. Components are determined by assignment to an activity area (a specific functional part of a settlement area) and period (a chronological and cultural classification). Each component is also assigned a list of activities, i.e., the types of activities that are directly documented within the component. Components are arbitrarily defined units; the decisive aspect in their definition is the clarity and understandability of the record of the event's results. In the AMCR, we do not envisage a detailed and exhaustive description of the archaeological finds belonging to each component; we understand finds only as specific attributes of components that help us to characterize the source material by which the component was recognized.
          • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

    • specializes class Fieldwork Event (akce) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#akce)
      Definition: An archaeological fieldwork event is a collection of archaeological finds and observations corresponding to a specific location (spatial delineation), originator (person, organization), time of execution, and method of research used. Events are divided into those derived from projects (project events) and those that stand alone (individual), i.e., those created without direct relation to a previously recorded project (e.g., retrospective recording). For defining an 'event', the archaeological research activity is crucial. An event may have one or more documentation units of different types. An event component is the spatial, chronological, and functional sum of findings from one event documentation unit.

      Definition: The Record of Individual Finds (AMCR-PAS) is used to collect information on individual finds made as part of archaeological projects, particularly from amateur collaborators of authorised archaeological organisations. The individual finds are linked directly to a specific project, are accompanied by photographic documentation, have their specific spatial delineation by coordinates, and include a description of the find itself. The AMCR system accepts data on finds only after they have been confirmed by the archaeologist responsible for the survey.

Document (dokument)

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#dokument
Label Document (dokument)
Definition A document is an element of documentation of archaeological fieldwork stored in the archives of the ARÚ and ARÚB. Similar information sources in other institutions are treated as external sources; unlike documents, we cannot provide their detailed metadata description or full-text version. The content of documents can be described through document components and finds (analogous to components and finds of archaeological records). Such a description is particularly useful for photographs and plans, whose content is always narrower than the content of the entire fieldwork event. Document parts link documents to other data classes. Each document part records at most one link to an event, site or project and any number of links to components. Documents (especially reports) sometimes contain information about fieldwork that is not reported in archaeological event records, or a link is not yet set up between the document and the event record. For these cases, an unidentified event data class is created in the AMCR in the form of extension information on the document part. In the case of aerial photographs, a link to the flight is usually also included within the document record.

dokument_cast

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument_cast
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#dokument_cast
Label dokument_cast
Hierarchy
  • profiles class dokument_cast (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument_cast)
    • specializes class Document (dokument) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument)
      Definition: A document is an element of documentation of archaeological fieldwork stored in the archives of the ARÚ and ARÚB. Similar information sources in other institutions are treated as external sources; unlike documents, we cannot provide their detailed metadata description or full-text version. The content of documents can be described through document components and finds (analogous to components and finds of archaeological records). Such a description is particularly useful for photographs and plans, whose content is always narrower than the content of the entire fieldwork event. Document parts link documents to other data classes. Each document part records at most one link to an event, site or project and any number of links to components. Documents (especially reports) sometimes contain information about fieldwork that is not reported in archaeological event records, or a link is not yet set up between the document and the event record. For these cases, an unidentified event data class is created in the AMCR in the form of extension information on the document part. In the case of aerial photographs, a link to the flight is usually also included within the document record.
      • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

dokumentacni_jednotka

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokumentacni_jednotka
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#dokumentacni_jednotka
Label dokumentacni_jednotka
Hierarchy
  • profiles class dokumentacni_jednotka (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokumentacni_jednotka)
    • specializes class Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#archeologicky_zaznam)
      Definition: Archaeological records are a collective term for two types of records - archaeological FIELDWORK EVENTS and SITES. The archaeological record is further subdivided into spatial units, the so-called documentation units. A documentation unit can be considered to be the entire area of an event, its part corresponding to a certain group of finds, or its part defined by the course of fieldwork (e.g. a specific trench). Components are linked to documentation units. Components are determined by assignment to an activity area (a specific functional part of a settlement area) and period (a chronological and cultural classification). Each component is also assigned a list of activities, i.e., the types of activities that are directly documented within the component. Components are arbitrarily defined units; the decisive aspect in their definition is the clarity and understandability of the record of the event's results. In the AMCR, we do not envisage a detailed and exhaustive description of the archaeological finds belonging to each component; we understand finds only as specific attributes of components that help us to characterize the source material by which the component was recognized.
      • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

  • profiles class extra_data (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#extra_data)
    • specializes class Document (dokument) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument)
      Definition: A document is an element of documentation of archaeological fieldwork stored in the archives of the ARÚ and ARÚB. Similar information sources in other institutions are treated as external sources; unlike documents, we cannot provide their detailed metadata description or full-text version. The content of documents can be described through document components and finds (analogous to components and finds of archaeological records). Such a description is particularly useful for photographs and plans, whose content is always narrower than the content of the entire fieldwork event. Document parts link documents to other data classes. Each document part records at most one link to an event, site or project and any number of links to components. Documents (especially reports) sometimes contain information about fieldwork that is not reported in archaeological event records, or a link is not yet set up between the document and the event record. For these cases, an unidentified event data class is created in the AMCR in the form of extension information on the document part. In the case of aerial photographs, a link to the flight is usually also included within the document record.
      • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

Fieldwork Event (akce)

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#akce
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#akce
Label Fieldwork Event (akce)
Definition An archaeological fieldwork event is a collection of archaeological finds and observations corresponding to a specific location (spatial delineation), originator (person, organization), time of execution, and method of research used. Events are divided into those derived from projects (project events) and those that stand alone (individual), i.e., those created without direct relation to a previously recorded project (e.g., retrospective recording). For defining an 'event', the archaeological research activity is crucial. An event may have one or more documentation units of different types. An event component is the spatial, chronological, and functional sum of findings from one event documentation unit.
Hierarchy
  • profiles class Fieldwork Event (akce) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#akce)
    Definition: An archaeological fieldwork event is a collection of archaeological finds and observations corresponding to a specific location (spatial delineation), originator (person, organization), time of execution, and method of research used. Events are divided into those derived from projects (project events) and those that stand alone (individual), i.e., those created without direct relation to a previously recorded project (e.g., retrospective recording). For defining an 'event', the archaeological research activity is crucial. An event may have one or more documentation units of different types. An event component is the spatial, chronological, and functional sum of findings from one event documentation unit.
    • specializes class Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#archeologicky_zaznam)
      Definition: Archaeological records are a collective term for two types of records - archaeological FIELDWORK EVENTS and SITES. The archaeological record is further subdivided into spatial units, the so-called documentation units. A documentation unit can be considered to be the entire area of an event, its part corresponding to a certain group of finds, or its part defined by the course of fieldwork (e.g. a specific trench). Components are linked to documentation units. Components are determined by assignment to an activity area (a specific functional part of a settlement area) and period (a chronological and cultural classification). Each component is also assigned a list of activities, i.e., the types of activities that are directly documented within the component. Components are arbitrarily defined units; the decisive aspect in their definition is the clarity and understandability of the record of the event's results. In the AMCR, we do not envisage a detailed and exhaustive description of the archaeological finds belonging to each component; we understand finds only as specific attributes of components that help us to characterize the source material by which the component was recognized.
      • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

Individual Find (samostatny_nalez)

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#samostatny_nalez
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#samostatny_nalez
Label Individual Find (samostatny_nalez)
Definition The Record of Individual Finds (AMCR-PAS) is used to collect information on individual finds made as part of archaeological projects, particularly from amateur collaborators of authorised archaeological organisations. The individual finds are linked directly to a specific project, are accompanied by photographic documentation, have their specific spatial delineation by coordinates, and include a description of the find itself. The AMCR system accepts data on finds only after they have been confirmed by the archaeologist responsible for the survey.

neident_akce

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#neident_akce
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#neident_akce
Label neident_akce
Hierarchy
  • profiles class neident_akce (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#neident_akce)
    • specializes class dokument_cast (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument_cast)
      • specializes class Document (dokument) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument)
        Definition: A document is an element of documentation of archaeological fieldwork stored in the archives of the ARÚ and ARÚB. Similar information sources in other institutions are treated as external sources; unlike documents, we cannot provide their detailed metadata description or full-text version. The content of documents can be described through document components and finds (analogous to components and finds of archaeological records). Such a description is particularly useful for photographs and plans, whose content is always narrower than the content of the entire fieldwork event. Document parts link documents to other data classes. Each document part records at most one link to an event, site or project and any number of links to components. Documents (especially reports) sometimes contain information about fieldwork that is not reported in archaeological event records, or a link is not yet set up between the document and the event record. For these cases, an unidentified event data class is created in the AMCR in the form of extension information on the document part. In the case of aerial photographs, a link to the flight is usually also included within the document record.
        • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

Site (lokalita)

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#lokalita
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#lokalita
Label Site (lokalita)
Definition A site is a collection of archaeological finds and observations corresponding to a specific location (spatial delineation), characteristic archaeological manifestation, and presumed past functional context. For defining a 'site', the form of the archaeological record (manifestation) is crucial. A site has just one documentation unit. A site component is the spatial, chronological, and functional sum of findings from a site.
Hierarchy
  • profiles class Site (lokalita) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#lokalita)
    Definition: A site is a collection of archaeological finds and observations corresponding to a specific location (spatial delineation), characteristic archaeological manifestation, and presumed past functional context. For defining a 'site', the form of the archaeological record (manifestation) is crucial. A site has just one documentation unit. A site component is the spatial, chronological, and functional sum of findings from a site.
    • specializes class Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#archeologicky_zaznam)
      Definition: Archaeological records are a collective term for two types of records - archaeological FIELDWORK EVENTS and SITES. The archaeological record is further subdivided into spatial units, the so-called documentation units. A documentation unit can be considered to be the entire area of an event, its part corresponding to a certain group of finds, or its part defined by the course of fieldwork (e.g. a specific trench). Components are linked to documentation units. Components are determined by assignment to an activity area (a specific functional part of a settlement area) and period (a chronological and cultural classification). Each component is also assigned a list of activities, i.e., the types of activities that are directly documented within the component. Components are arbitrarily defined units; the decisive aspect in their definition is the clarity and understandability of the record of the event's results. In the AMCR, we do not envisage a detailed and exhaustive description of the archaeological finds belonging to each component; we understand finds only as specific attributes of components that help us to characterize the source material by which the component was recognized.
      • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

tvar

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#tvar
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#tvar
Label tvar
Hierarchy
  • profiles class tvar (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#tvar)
    • specializes class Document (dokument) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokument)
      Definition: A document is an element of documentation of archaeological fieldwork stored in the archives of the ARÚ and ARÚB. Similar information sources in other institutions are treated as external sources; unlike documents, we cannot provide their detailed metadata description or full-text version. The content of documents can be described through document components and finds (analogous to components and finds of archaeological records). Such a description is particularly useful for photographs and plans, whose content is always narrower than the content of the entire fieldwork event. Document parts link documents to other data classes. Each document part records at most one link to an event, site or project and any number of links to components. Documents (especially reports) sometimes contain information about fieldwork that is not reported in archaeological event records, or a link is not yet set up between the document and the event record. For these cases, an unidentified event data class is created in the AMCR in the form of extension information on the document part. In the case of aerial photographs, a link to the flight is usually also included within the document record.
      • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)

vyskovy_bod

Profiled class IRI(s) https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#vyskovy_bod
IRI https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema/profile#vyskovy_bod
Label vyskovy_bod
Hierarchy
  • profiles class vyskovy_bod (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#vyskovy_bod)
    • specializes class Archaeological Documentation Point (adb) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#adb)
      Definition: Archaeological Documentation Points (ADP) are an expanded description of 'trench' type documentation units that capture more detailed information about the circumstances of an excavation. Their main specificity is the option of assigning information about the captured stratigraphic horizons and their precise positional and elevation determination by means of so-called elevation points. These data allow reconstructing archaeological terrains and predicting the degree of their preservation in the surrounding area. The ADP registration system is based on the principles set by L. Hrdlička, who compiled and maintained the ADP Map for the Prague Conservation Area for a long time. The data in the AMCR are directly related to this registration system.
      • specializes class dokumentacni_jednotka (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#dokumentacni_jednotka)
        • specializes class Archaeological Record (archeologicky_zaznam) (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#archeologicky_zaznam)
          Definition: Archaeological records are a collective term for two types of records - archaeological FIELDWORK EVENTS and SITES. The archaeological record is further subdivided into spatial units, the so-called documentation units. A documentation unit can be considered to be the entire area of an event, its part corresponding to a certain group of finds, or its part defined by the course of fieldwork (e.g. a specific trench). Components are linked to documentation units. Components are determined by assignment to an activity area (a specific functional part of a settlement area) and period (a chronological and cultural classification). Each component is also assigned a list of activities, i.e., the types of activities that are directly documented within the component. Components are arbitrarily defined units; the decisive aspect in their definition is the clarity and understandability of the record of the event's results. In the AMCR, we do not envisage a detailed and exhaustive description of the archaeological finds belonging to each component; we understand finds only as specific attributes of components that help us to characterize the source material by which the component was recognized.
          • specializes class amcr (https://amcr.aiscr.cz/schema#amcr)
